  <title>Roles</title>
   
   <indexterm>
      <primary>ESB</primary>
      <secondary>development roles</secondary>
   </indexterm>
   
  <para>
     A number of common roles have emerged in the SOA space, indicating the responsibilities of certain individuals.
     Having a common language to describe these roles (just like with Java EE) allows the industry to communicate
     the intentions around tools, training courses, employee resum√© requirements, etc. The following roles
     are pertinent:
  </para>
  
  <section>
      <title>Business-logic developer</title>
      <para>
      A business logic developer writes the individual service implementations without
      worrying about
      <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
               <para>where the service is to be deployed,</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>where the services it depends on are deployed,</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>non-functional requirements such as security, reliability</para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
      </para>
  </section>
  
  <section>
      <title>Service orchestrator</title>
      <para>
      Service orchestrators
      <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
               <para>
           integrate services into higher level services and
        </para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>
          specify transactional requirements across the resultant work flow.
        </para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
      </para>
  </section>
  
  <section>
      <title>Service deployers</title>
      <para>
      Service deployers
      <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
               <para>
          decide on where services are deployed,          
        </para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>
          register services with the registry,
        </para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>
          and assign authorization requirements to services.  
        </para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
      </para>
  </section>
  
  
  <section>
      <title>Administrators</title>
      <para>
       Administrators are responsible for ensuring that the 
       <itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
             <para>nodes hosting services are available,</para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
             <para>the ESB infrastructure is available, and</para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
             <para>system load is manageable (i.e. performance is adequate)</para>
          </listitem>
       </itemizedlist>
    </para>
  </section>
  
</section>